# Dependencies
node_modules/
.venv/
# Root node_modules symlink -> frontend/node_modules (so plugin TSX
# outside the Vite project can resolve bare imports like "react"). The
# trailing-slash ``node_modules/`` rule above matches real dirs but not
# this root symlink (git treats the symlink as a file), so anchor it.
/node_modules

# Build output
frontend/dist/

# Python
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*.pyo
*.egg-info/
dist/
build/

# Environment
.env
.env.local

# OS
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# IDE / Editor
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo
*~

# Logs
*.log
.zed/

# Large model files (too big for GitHub)
models/
*.gguf

# Per-user chat data
data/

# Frontend plugin normalisation target. The entrypoint /
# ``backend/sync_plugins.sh`` copies each ``plugins/<id>/frontend/``
# here so Vite can resolve modules against the frontend project.
# These are generated artefacts (not authored by hand) so we ignore
# them. The ``.gitkeep`` is re-included via negation so the empty
# dir stays tracked for the sync target.
#
# This is safe because Tailwind is gone from this project. Vite's
# ``import.meta.glob`` and the global stylesheet (``components.css``
# in ``src/styles/``) don't read ``.gitignore`` — they walk the
# filesystem directly. So the plugin TSX is still bundled by Vite
# and its CSS classes are still in the bundle, regardless of this
# ignore rule. (The reason it USED to be untracked-only is that
# Tailwind v4's scanner respected git's exclusion and would skip
# these files, dropping their classes from the CSS. That constraint
# no longer applies.)
frontend/src/plugins/user/*
!frontend/src/plugins/user/.gitkeep
